3️⃣ Service (Transactional)
@Service
public class AccountService {

    @Autowired
    private AccountRepository repo;

    @Transactional
    public void withdraw(Long id, double amount) {

        Account acc = repo.findByIdForUpdate(id); // Row locked

        if (acc.getBalance() < amount) {
            throw new RuntimeException("Insufficient balance");
        }

        acc.setBalance(acc.getBalance() - amount);

        repo.save(acc); // Update happens while lock held
    }
}

🧪 What happens in concurrency?
Transaction 1	Transaction 2
Locks row (FOR UPDATE)	Tries to lock same row
Updating...	Waits ⏳
Commit	Lock released
—	Now proceeds
⚖️ Optimistic vs Pessimistic
Feature	Optimistic (@Version)	Pessimistic (FOR UPDATE)
Lock timing	At commit	Immediately
Conflict handling	Retry on failure	Prevent conflict
Performance	Faster	Slower (blocking)
Use case	Rare conflicts	Frequent conflicts
Deadlock risk	No	Yes ⚠️
⚠️ Risks

Deadlocks possible

Threads may wait long → slow performance

Use only when data must be strictly protected

