Tx2 Updated Balance to 500
Tx1 Second Read: 1000   ✅ No non-repeatable read

🧠 Interview Explanation (Golden Answer)

READ_COMMITTED → prevents dirty read but allows non-repeatable read

REPEATABLE_READ → prevents dirty + non-repeatable read

SERIALIZABLE → prevents phantom read also

Higher isolation = more locks + less performance

Deadlock Retry (Spring Boot / JPA)

When two transactions lock resources in opposite order, deadlock happens. Database aborts one transaction → you must retry automatically.

Goal: If deadlock occurs → retry transaction few times → succeed without user error.

1. Detect Deadlock Exception

Common DB exceptions:

MySQL → DeadlockLoserDataAccessException

JPA → PessimisticLockingFailureException

Hibernate → LockAcquisitionException

Spring translates all into DeadlockLoserDataAccessException (most common).

2. Add Spring Retry Dependency

pom.xml

<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.retry</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-retry</artifactId>
</dependency>

<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-aspects</artifactId>
</dependency>

3. Enable Retry
@Configuration
@EnableRetry
public class RetryConfig {
}

4. Retryable Transaction (Deadlock Safe)
@Service
public class AccountService {

    @Autowired
    private AccountRepository repo;

    @Transactional
    @Retryable(
        value = DeadlockLoserDataAccessException.class,
        maxAttempts = 3,
        backoff = @Backoff(delay = 200)
    )
    public void transfer(Long fromId, Long toId, double amount) {

        Account from = repo.findByIdForUpdate(fromId);
        Account to   = repo.findByIdForUpdate(toId);

        if (from.getBalance() < amount)
            throw new RuntimeException("Insufficient balance");

        from.setBalance(from.getBalance() - amount);
        to.setBalance(to.getBalance() + amount);

        repo.save(from);
        repo.save(to);
    }

    @Recover
    public void recover(DeadlockLoserDataAccessException ex,
                        Long fromId, Long toId, double amount) {

        System.out.println("❌ Deadlock retry failed after 3 attempts");
        throw ex;
    }
}

5. Repository with Pessimistic Lock
@Repository
public interface AccountRepository extends JpaRepository<Account, Long> {

    @Lock(LockModeType.PESSIMISTIC_WRITE)
    @Query("select a from Account a where a.id = :id")
    Account findByIdForUpdate(Long id);
}

6. How Retry Works
Transaction 1 locks A → wants B
Transaction 2 locks B → wants A
→ DEADLOCK

DB kills one transaction
Spring catches DeadlockLoserDataAccessException
Retry automatically runs again
Second attempt succeeds

7. Best Practices

✔ Always retry deadlock (2–3 times enough)
✔ Keep transaction short
✔ Access rows in same order (avoid deadlock)
✔ Use PESSIMISTIC_WRITE only when needed
✔ Add small backoff delay (100–300 ms)

8. Interview Answer (Short)

Deadlock occurs when two transactions wait for each other's locks. Database aborts one transaction. In Spring Boot, we handle it using @Retryable(DeadlockLoserDataAccessException.class) so the transaction retries automatically and succeeds without user failure.

